    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-06-22T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-06-22T05:00:00-05:00" n="406"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d406">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890G.24/35: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Iraq</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Farrell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Baghdad</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-06-22T13:00:00+03:00"
                            >June 22, 1942—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 6:37 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>127. At the instance of the United States military Iranian mission I have engaged
                    in discussions with the Iraqi Ministry of Finance with a view to obtaining
                    exemption from customs and other dues on materials imported by the mission into
                    Iraq as well as goods in transit. Ministry suggest that note be tendered through
                    Foreign Office requesting “That immunities and privileges in jurisdictional and
                    fiscal matters including freedom from taxation which are now enjoyed by British
                    forces in Iraq according to treaty be extended to the United States military
                    mission and its agencies functioning under orders from United States Government”
                    and listing all agencies so functioning under the mission. While Iraqi
                    Government is apparently willing to grant the desired extention to bona fide
                    agencies of the War Department clearly financed by the United States Government
                    and manned by personnel subject to military jurisdiction, question is raised
                    regarding the status with the War Department of Pan American Airways and Douglas
                    Aircraft Corporation. Although latter does not function in Iraq but in Iran,
                    military mission desires all agencies covered here.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Farrell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
